<rate>4</rate>< review>
I have read about concerns about parking and the towel service. Today was my first workout there and found the facility to have ample parking and I always bring my own towels to the gym.
Today was a leg workout and the facility (in my opinion) lacks some leg equipment like a good leg extension and lying leg curl machine. I find the Hoist equipment to lack in full range of motion.
The weight room does have all  Hammer Strength for chest, back and shoulders. It also has a turf section for athletes.
Nice gym; except for trashing of legs.<//review>

< Review>
I loved the service and the work, I never had a complaint and I couldn't believe the negative comments. However, today I was so disappointed with the professionalism. I went in for a manicure with gel and there were only 3 customers including myself in the salon so it wasn't busy. While getting my manicure, the girl was going so fast she clipped my skin, which caught me by surprise and she did apologize so I let it go. She proceeded with my gel and by the 3-4 coats I could tell she was struggling but I didn't want to give her a hard time so I patiently waited (she wasn't done anyways). She continued to pack on the coats, and brush the sides of my nails with the acetone. When she said she was done I couldn't believe my eyes. After the hour and a half, my nail beds were messy and I had some spots without nail polish, to say the least it wasn't worth the $26 she was trying to charge me. She attempted to file the nail polish off my skin and clip whatever was left over. When I expressed my concern she tried to say that it was because my nails were very oily. She called 2 people over and I have no idea what they were saying among themselves, she then tried to charge me $15 for the manicure. She offered to take my gel off but she'd still charge me the $15, one of the employees joked around and said, "maybe next time". If I could, I would give zero stars, I was very disappointed and I cannot believe that neither of them spoke up and agreed that the work was terrible! I WILL NOT BE RETURNING! I rather take the 15 minute drive and go to Nail World in Reedley.</Review>

<review>I‚Äôve been in the event industry for 30 years and this is one of the best event companies I‚Äôve had the pleasure of working with.  When reading the reviews and seeing how many people from a single event have written numerous bad reviews to affect the overall rating of this company says one thing, they must have numerous people write reviews to lower the rating because there are not enough unhappy customers overall.  It‚Äôs been my experience that some people who go over budget, look for ways to recoup and complaining about vendors and demanding refunds happens.  When they don‚Äôt get what they demand, they write bad reviews to hurt the company.  Yes, a rental company rents USED equipment, just like a rented car is not new.  Damage comes from customers abusing equipment, not from a company mistreating their investment.  Linen stains are unfortunately something every company misses.  Nobody is going to send out linens they know have stains.  I have used many upscale linen services and even they miss an occasional stain.  Dishes and glassware can appear ‚Äúdirty‚Äù with spots from sanitizer but many rental companies wash hundreds or thousands of dishes and unless it‚Äôs dried on food, it is likely that its residue and if you rent it expecting new, perfect condition equipment, you may need to go buy it new.  Having everyone you know write bad reviews, only makes you look like a spoiled child that didn‚Äôt get their way and is trying to be vindictive.

P.S.   When people say their delivery was late, unless you have to postpone the event because it wasn‚Äôt there on the day of the event, if you get your order the day before or a few hours before the event, its not late.  Event rental companies may have 10, 20, 60 or more events to cover on a single day and everyone wants to get their stuff first but everyone can‚Äôt be first.

< text>
Just happened on to this place in Livermore. It's got the look and feel of a traditional Italian cafe and yet has an American flare to it. I had a cappuccino and my wife a macchiato both equally delicious, flavorful but not overpowering. The baristas are skilled and polite. Also had a slice of their apple pie... it's a must get. Overall a great place to visit and just hangout. Weather it's to hide in the little cubby room and work on your computer, sit by a window and read one if their many books, or just to chat with a friend. It's worth the visit.<//text>

< user_name>
Eric Rhodes</user_name>
<Gmap_id>0x808fe79f00f13da1:0x44d16fc2c7d86620< /Gmap_id><Pictures>None<//Pictures><rate>5<//rate><time>1581114997077<//time>< text>
Espresso Rosetta is a pretty fantastic coffee and tea shop for those who appreciate well balanced flavored lattes, a relaxing atmosphere, and an open feel.

It has fairly high ceilings which is nice and it has a separate room that is a pretty good solo study area for students.

The only downsides are there are few electrical outlets in the main room, the tables are a bit small if there are two people who each need a laptop, and parking during busy downtown times can be difficult, i.e. you'll have to park a block or two away.

All in all though EspRo found a good fit in Livermore even with Panama near by. The different more quiet atmosphere will be attractive to those who prefer more silent places to drink their brews.< /text>

< text>
This Independent Coffeehouse Translates Rather Well

When the cookiecutter coffeehouse has got you down and the loud tropical coffeehouse is full of improperly medicated tweens arguing about self-immolation as art, Espresso Rosetta is an oasis of calm. Their understated design and superb eye for local art pair well with solid skills in the caffeinated beverage department.

Whether you're looking for a pot of Earl Grey or an Americano (never bitter!) to go, Espresso Rosetta is the key to filtering out the babble of an increasingly noisy world.

Do yourself a favor and stop in today.<//text>

< Review>
My 2018 Toyota Prius was recently stolen and subsequently wrecked. My insurance approved me to bring the car to the body shop of my choice. Since I am new to the Bay Area I wasn‚Äôt familiar with the area. So, I spent a couple hours researching body shops within a 15-mile radius. I finally decided that, based on reviews, Moeller Bros was the best place for my car.
My experience was positive from the beginning. Stacy answered my initial phone call and was professional and helpful. She offered to pick my car up at the Palace Garage tow yard for FREE. However my experience only got better when my case was assigned to Carlos. He inspected the car and found substantial damage BEYOND the preliminary Insurance estimate. Although the damage appeared to be minor to me, they determined that the vehicle was totaled. This is significant because they did what was in MY best interest. They easily could have written it up as a ‚Äúhigh-cost repair‚Äù, just below the totaled threshold, and made a killing in labor, parts, and storage. But they didn‚Äôt! This place has a rare integrity and let me say it was refreshing. Now I am in the process of buying another car, and couldn‚Äôt be happier. I will always be grateful to the staff at Moeller Bros for their professionalism and doing the right thing.<//Review>

<rating>5<//rating>< user_id>
108931710912566673572<//user_id>
< review>
Amazing seafood, fantastic and friendly staff, great atmosphere.

Unsurprisingly, it is expensive.  But you get what you pay for.

The crab is doused in some butter and a little bit of garlic, very tasty albeit messy.  Most people use the excess crab butter to dip the bread in.

The muscles and shrimp come with butter to dip them in.  The shrimp was good, but not nearly as delicious as the muscles.  Very buttery and firm, not fishy or slimy at all.  As someone who has never had muscles before, I highly recommend also trying the muscles (pass on the shrimp).

Very pleased overall.  I'm not a huge fan of cooked seafood, but I really enjoyed this place.  If you are looking for seafood in SF, this is the place to go to.</review>

</dataset><record>
<userid>110227997871032016650</userid><user_name>Mar Vy< /user_name><Date>1519878061525<//Date><Rating>3< /Rating>< Review>
Intrigued by the World Famous Dungeness Killer Crab and craving for seafood, we decided to have dinner here. We arrived around 8:30 pm, our reservation was set for 9:00 pm.  I thought we had to wait till 9pm but we didn't, they seated us right away.  The restaurant was busy and there were people waiting to be seated.  The ambiance was a little loud.  If you look up towards the ceiling,  you will see decorations of colorful crabs and nets.  We sat by the window so our view was the water and the boat dock.  The waiter took our order, we got shrimps, Dungeness Crab, and clams with fettuccine.

~Drinks~
I took a sip of the Strawberry Mojito, I didn't like it much because it lacked the strawberry flavor.  Instead, I asked for a glass of Riesling (white wine) which tasted better.

~Food~
After ordering,  we were given two loafs of bread.  We used the vinegar and oil to dip the bread in.  The waiter gave us a bib that had a picture of a crab on it.  First, we got the roasted shrimps (12 pieces)  which was served in an iron skillet and it came with a side of warm sauce that tasted like a mixture of butter and lemon. The shrimps were very small; it tasted good with the sauce.  Next was the Dungeness Killer Crab (whole crab - 2 plus pounds) that was roasted in their secret garlic sauce.   I was really looking forward to this dish but I was disappointed because I couldn't taste the garlic. The last one is the Clams with garlic sauce and fettuccine pasta.  The pasta was thick and a little hard but I enjoyed the sauce.

~Customer Service~
They cleared out the plates quickly after we finished our food.  The hostess was nice and friendly.

~Tip~
Call for restaurant reservation

~Notes~
-Crab cracker tool is already placed on the table.<//Review>

<userid>106991404813587388501</userid>< Date>
1582752912940<//Date>
< GmapID>
0x808580fce4c03df5:0x813eb737327fef71</GmapID>
< rating>
4</rating>
< text>
Reservations are a must. Expensive & limited parking. Wheelchair accessible. Gluten free options available. Super sweet servers. The food is delicious even for people like myself who don't frequent seafood. 10 out of 10 love their garlic fries. This place is ideal for small groups, which I'd recommend ordering the large shareable platters. They easily feed 4 people per platter. Highly recommend using public transit to avoid the hassle to get here. Not a fan of super crowded or tourist populated areas, but there are definitely a few places worth surfing the crowds to get to~ üë•ü§ôüèÑ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è</text>

<text>Intrigued by the World Famous Dungeness Killer Crab and craving for seafood, we decided to have dinner here. We arrived around 8:30 pm, our reservation was set for 9:00 pm.  I thought we had to wait till 9pm but we didn't, they seated us right away.  The restaurant was busy and there were people waiting to be seated.  The ambiance was a little loud.  If you look up towards the ceiling,  you will see decorations of colorful crabs and nets.  We sat by the window so our view was the water and the boat dock.  The waiter took our order, we got shrimps, Dungeness Crab, and clams with fettuccine.

~Drinks~
I took a sip of the Strawberry Mojito, I didn't like it much because it lacked the strawberry flavor.  Instead, I asked for a glass of Riesling (white wine) which tasted better.

~Food~
After ordering,  we were given two loafs of bread.  We used the vinegar and oil to dip the bread in.  The waiter gave us a bib that had a picture of a crab on it.  First, we got the roasted shrimps (12 pieces)  which was served in an iron skillet and it came with a side of warm sauce that tasted like a mixture of butter and lemon. The shrimps were very small; it tasted good with the sauce.  Next was the Dungeness Killer Crab (whole crab - 2 plus pounds) that was roasted in their secret garlic sauce.   I was really looking forward to this dish but I was disappointed because I couldn't taste the garlic. The last one is the Clams with garlic sauce and fettuccine pasta.  The pasta was thick and a little hard but I enjoyed the sauce.

~Customer Service~
They cleared out the plates quickly after we finished our food.  The hostess was nice and friendly.

~Tip~
Call for restaurant reservation

~Notes~
-Crab cracker tool is already placed on the table.</text>< Response>

I didn't get served for about 10 minutes after being shown to my table, not even a hello or offering drinks. I did not receive service until I asked for it.
I don't really factor that into this review though, food is the important part.

I had the crab chowder in a sourdough bowl, and I would say it was average.
Temperature was perfect, however other things were not.

Presentation was great, as you can see.

Overall, for 15 dollars, you are likely better served getting chowder from elsewhere.

< Rate>

<text>My experience was just okay.

I didn't get served for about 10 minutes after being shown to my table, not even a hello or offering drinks. I did not receive service until I asked for it.
I don't really factor that into this review though, food is the important part.

I had the crab chowder in a sourdough bowl, and I would say it was average.
Temperature was perfect, however other things were not.
For a chowder, it was incredibly thin, lacking the thickness you would expect from a good chowder. I would say it was closer to a soup than a chowder.
Flavour wise, unfortunately it was lacking. While it had many ingredients, none of these flavours really stood out or were very obvious. Nearly flavourless. For a seafood chowder, you would expect more of an ocean flavour, however, that was not present here.
Presentation was great, as you can see.

Overall, for 15 dollars, you are likely better served getting chowder from elsewhere.
Unfortunate, because the view of the bay from the restaurant is excellent.</text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPpFNRWDzY9qAAerBKECQRVkRcVEUAz14HPUIUh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><Resp>{'time': 1554501362494, 'text': "Thank you for your feedback, Wesley.\n\nWe're sorry to hear that you were not completely satisfied with your dining experience. < Review>
I gave this restaurant 3-star because while the crab there is good, the service is so-so to say the best and price is kind of expensive. We did not feel like welcomed guests at all. Someone came to take order and disappeared. No one ever cared to ask how we were doing or how the food was. Understand most customers are tourists, like us. But with reviews from Google and Yelp, locals and tourists should be equally important to a restaurant. We will try a different crab house next time in town, for sure.</Review>

< rate>
2</rate>
<gmapID>0x808580fce4c03df5:0x813eb737327fef71< /gmapID>< text>
To start, it is San Francisco and its very busy. Still, from the moment you walk in, its rushed, chaotic and impossible to walk without bumping into anything.

To many tables in a very tight places makes eating any meal not very enjoyable. Maybe the concentration should be less tables and better customer experience rather than what felt like the, "burn and turn" system. Staff is friendly, but you really cant blame them. They can only work with what they have.

The food was average, the price not so.

The Crab Pot in Pikes Market in Seattle, does a much better job of providing a dine by the pier experience. Where the food is much more  worth the price on the menu.

Fastest  $75 buck lunch ever. Not to mention I still picked up something to eat 10 minutes after walking on the pier.

You live and you learn. Hope this helps someone else.<//text>

I made a reservation here by using Open Table and got right in easily while there was a line on a Saturday. The restaurant is extremely tight and even more so when they place you at a booth along the walkway of the waiters going to the kitchen. The tables at the booths are very small and then they give you very long plates. It doesn‚Äôt make sense. I ordered a tea and the Waite brings me a coke. I never order sodas so I‚Äôm pretty sure I didn‚Äôt misspeak. When I asked for a tea instead, he looked confused and asked if I still wanted it. I said no so he brought out the tea and left the coke in the table. I ordered a crab melt, my friend ordered fried fish and her husband ordered crab legs. My melt was so full of onions that I had a pile of them sitting on the side. There wasn‚Äôt that much crab meat but tons of cheese. It was more like a grilled cheese sandwich with some crab. My friend ate her fish and began feeling sick. Her husband ate his crab and said he never tasted much of a flavor. There was nothing special to the legs to set them apart from a mom and pop place somewhere else. We got in the car and my friend felt even worse. Once she got home, she threw up her fish. Not sure what was going on but from how tight the restaurant is, the bad decision to use long plates for small tables, tasteless crab, piles of onions, and bad fish, we won‚Äôt be back.< /review>

< Text>
I recently just got back from visiting San Francisco. I am a food fanatic. I will base a trip around food! This trip was based around crab. I read the reviews on probably a 100 restaurants and picked the Crab House on 39. I made a reservation for 2 with a window table with a view. I could see Alcatraz and the Golden Gate bridge. Ordered calamari as a appetizer. Amazing. Ordered 2 whole crabs and a order of garlic fries. Amazing! The medium order of garlic fries is huge. My wife and I could not eat all the fries. The decor needs a little updating. Service was good. Price for all that with tip was around $120. A little pricey.Other than that, we had a amazing romantic evening! Will go back one day!</Text>

< Review>
The Crab House is located on the 2nd level on the right. We dined here for lunch, it was very crowded. We waited about 25 minutes.

My wife and I ordered the pasta dishes with crab, we didn't feel like getting our hands messy trying to get the crab meat out if the shells.

Both dishes was filled with large pieces of crab meat. The sauce was creamy and full of flavour.

The service was quick. Some of the staff were friendly and helpful and some were not.

Also, they do validate parking if you're parked directly across the street in the 5 level garage. But make sure they do it. I gave our waiter our parking ticket but when we paid , it wasn't validated! It's $10/ hr.</Review>

<rating>4</rating>< Review>
The food was delicious, service was great and the views were spectacular. It was fun to watch the bartender turn out drinks like a machine and the staff working together to provide quick, friendly service. I love crab and was really excited about the menu. We shared a crab chowder bread bowl and 1 pound of the famous Dungeness crab. It was plenty for the two of us so I'm glad we didn't order the "shareable" 3 pounds of crab. <Gmap_id>0x808580fce4c03df5:0x813eb737327fef71< /Gmap_id><name>tanya R<//name><userid>107330830635135982555< /userid><Review>I have not written a review before, but I was compelled to share this ridiculously rude and disappointing experience with The Crab House management. Our group of 42 found our ideal restaurant choice in the Fisherman‚Äôs Wharf area. I worked with Cody, Manager (seemingly very helpful), to create a fixed $50 banquet menu, shared our RSVP headcount, and submitted the required written banquet reservation form 7 days prior to our group event, guaranteed with my credit card.  Cody emailed 7 days prior, ‚ÄúPerfect, I have everything I need. Look forward to seeing you next Saturday.‚Äù

Less than 24 hours before our reservation, on the way to our airport flight to SF, he calls to inform us that The Crab House unfortunately cannot honor the reservation due to capacity challenges (we would occupy 1/3 of the space on a Saturday afternoon).  Are you effing kidding???  What type of restaurant would ethically do this?  We already had an off peak hour reservation at 4:30, so I offered to shorten our meal duration from 120 minutes to 90 minutes and move it up to 4pm.  Or break us up into 3 groups for seating. They remained faintly apologetic but inflexible, only offering us walk-in status, not even on the reservation slate.  Nor did he offer to make any effort to arrange substitute reservations at their sister restaurants and placed blame upon being uninformed of the restaurant owner‚Äôs ‚Äúnew policy.‚Äù They were obviously not willing to make exceptions through this policy to serve willing patrons through the transition.

Our group of families ended up having a fast food dinner at the Ferry Building. Embarrassed by this disastrous dining situation, I would absolutely not recommend The Crab House to anyone and will encourage our group to anti-crusade against this and their associated establishments. Their level of unaccommodating, non-service to prospective patrons is absurd, shameful, and unjustifiable.  Hopefully others seeking to have a moderately sized group dinner here will be dissuaded from wasting time arranging an event, at risk for breach of contract or other dubious practices.< /Review>< Date>

< Text>
The food was delicious, service was great and the views were spectacular. It was fun to watch the bartender turn out drinks like a machine and the staff working together to provide quick, friendly service. I love crab and was really excited about the menu. We shared a crab chowder bread bowl and 1 pound of the famous Dungeness crab. It was plenty for the two of us so I'm glad we didn't order the "shareable" 3 pounds of crab. The reason for 4 stars instead of 5 is because it was pretty pricey not to come with any sides, salad, bread, etc., the chowder was luke warm and could've used a bit more flavor, and I would've liked to have some lemon and plain drawn butter for my crab but I was too embarrassed to ask since it's cooked with butter and garlic. I may try other things on the menu but we'll probably check out the other restaurants in the area before going back.<//Text>

<Name>tanya R</Name>< review>
I have not written a review before, but I was compelled to share this ridiculously rude and disappointing experience with The Crab House management. Our group of 42 found our ideal restaurant choice in the Fisherman‚Äôs Wharf area. I worked with Cody, Manager (seemingly very helpful), to create a fixed $50 banquet menu, shared our RSVP headcount, and submitted the required written banquet reservation form 7 days prior to our group event, guaranteed with my credit card.  Cody emailed 7 days prior, ‚ÄúPerfect, I have everything I need. Look forward to seeing you next Saturday.‚Äù

Less than 24 hours before our reservation, on the way to our airport flight to SF, he calls to inform us that The Crab House unfortunately cannot honor the reservation due to capacity challenges (we would occupy 1/3 of the space on a Saturday afternoon).  Are you effing kidding???  What type of restaurant would ethically do this?  We already had an off peak hour reservation at 4:30, so I offered to shorten our meal duration from 120 minutes to 90 minutes and move it up to 4pm.  Or break us up into 3 groups for seating. They remained faintly apologetic but inflexible, only offering us walk-in status, not even on the reservation slate.  Nor did he offer to make any effort to arrange substitute reservations at their sister restaurants and placed blame upon being uninformed of the restaurant owner‚Äôs ‚Äúnew policy.‚Äù They were obviously not willing to make exceptions through this policy to serve willing patrons through the transition.

Our group of families ended up having a fast food dinner at the Ferry Building. Embarrassed by this disastrous dining situation, I would absolutely not recommend The Crab House to anyone and will encourage our group to anti-crusade against this and their associated establishments. Their level of unaccommodating, non-service to prospective patrons is absurd, shameful, and unjustifiable.  Hopefully others seeking to have a moderately sized group dinner here will be dissuaded from wasting time arranging an event, at risk for breach of contract or other dubious practices.< /review>

<name>Sandy B</name><Review>We visited the Crab House on a Saturday night at 9:00pm, for a birthday dinner.  We had reservations so there was no wait and we were seated immediately. The dress is casual and the atmosphere is lively, so don‚Äôt expect dim lights with candlelight and white tablecloths. For the 4 of us we ordered the Too Two Crab and it was enough for all of us. The crab and marinade was absolutely delicious! I salivate just thinking about it.  We also ordered the large size garlic fries. The fries were well seasoned and very good but I would recommend getting the medium serving instead because the large is enormous and there was so much left over.  We did have one problem when paying for our bill. Our credit card was not returned after paying. When my husband hunted down the waitress, she had originally charged our bill and erroneously charged the table next to us on our credit card.  The problem was quickly rectified, but I wonder if we would have lost our credit card if my husband had not realized it was missing. Another thing that bothered my husband, that while he was signing for the credit card charge, the waitress stood right over him while calculating the tip. We felt that was highly inappropriate. <userid>106948099488847378474</userid><Name>Brad Seehawer< /Name><Time>1272504175993<//Time><Rating>4</Rating>< Review>
Even though I'm not from the city, it's pretty obvious that you shouldn't go to the city's biggest tourist attraction for a good meal. The multitude of positive reviews on Yelp made me take a chance on Crab House.

The place is sort of out of the way on the pier, and they were happy to accommodate my reservation for eight later that night. Service was extraordinarily quick throughout the night, with single-digit minutes transpiring between placing orders and receiving our food, though I would think that a place called Crab House would have plenty of crab ready to go.

We started with two orders of garlic fries for the table, and the serving size was plenty large enough for everyone to have a share. The fries were only so-so, but the big blast of garlic no small consolation.

I grabbed a bowl of crab chowder, too. I thought the proportion of vegetables (carrot, corn, and potato) were almost too much for the small cup of chowder, preventing the crab (what should have been the star) to shine through.

The giant 6.5 lbs platter of crab we ordered was listed as serving four on the menu, but it fed five well. The garlic butter provided good coverage, though I could have appreciated a side of said butter for dipping. The cast iron griddle on which it was served was so hot that it provided a rich flavor to the meat.

As I walked past one of the many chain seafood restaurants on the Wharf, I wondered if they used fresh seafood or worked from the same suppliers as the rest of their locations in other parts of the country. I wasn't about to find out. You can do a whole lot worse on the Wharf, and - though a little expensive - Crab House lives up to its name.<//Review>

None</pictures>

<name>Travis A<//name><Text>The food was delicious! The atmosphere was "okay"; for that price it needs to looks a little more stylish, or at least intentional. It just didn't have that 25 dollar plate appeal, you know? Speaking of the appearance, the unisex bathroom was pretty gross. The waiter was "okay" - he was nice, but he forgot my water (table of 3) and he also seemed to have abandoned us for a while.
Also. THE CRAB CAKES ARE WAY TOO SMALL for the price they are. I never mind spending more than usual when it comes to seafood, but crab cakes that are the size of a half dollar is just a sad thing.  - This is especially disappointing when it costs 38 half dollars to buy them...
But again. The food and even the tiny crab cakes is very tasty, and the light sauce that they come on top of is DELICIOUS.
all in all the food is good , if I haven't mentioned that,  and although it's not the cleanest place it is a classic. You definitely want to eat here if you can afford it.

Okay another thing to note because I'm looking at their menu now that I'm home: WHY DO THEY INCLUDE "AN ADDITIONAL 4.9% TO ALL CHECKS to OFFSET THE COSTS OF DOING BUSINESS AND GOVERNMENT MANDATED EXPENSES"???  - - - One's cost of doing business is their cost of doing business. Not mine.. How does that even make sense?? - You pay for your cost of doing business with the business that you do. *Meaning, you prepare and sell food and serve alcohol. ...If you aren't covering business expenses with what you're doing, than you are failing. <user_id>108453675463629554167< /user_id><Resp>None<//Resp>< Name>
Karen V Chin</Name>
<Review>Came here for a double birthday party. Really pricey for what was being served. Definitely geared to tourists.  We ordered two Killer Crab Feasts (4 servings or 2 medium sized Dungeness Crabs per Feast) with secret garlic sauce (which didn't have much of a garlic taste).

Steamed Mussels, Caesar Salad. Bruschetta. All average tasting. Garlic Noodles (that didn't have much garlic flavor). Service was slow. The Pineapple Mojitos were weak (for $11.95/glass I expect some alcohol).

The place was crowded with tourists and the wait was long for them. On the plus side, the view was nice. Crab House let us bring in our two birthday cakes for us to serve and did not charge a cake cutting fee. They validate parking for 1 hr during lunch and 2 hrs during dinner hours.

We came for lunch and even with 1 hr validation parking with still $18. Again, for what we ate and what this place charges for crab, not worth going back. There are many other places in San Francisco that serves Dungeness crab in garlic sauce that are better tasting, cost less and don't have to pay such an outrageous price to park.</Review>< gmapID>
